    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>
                    <salute>My Lord</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I should have done myself the honor of writing sooner; if I had not in vain
                    waited for an answer about the moose Deer, from the friend I applied to. I must
                    no longer defer sending my gratefull thanks for the last instances of y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Grace's friendship, which I can never forget.</p>
                <p>Inclosed in six pacquets is my account of the Patagonians.<note type="editorial">Possibly  an early version of Pennant's <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0033">
                                <hi rend="italic">Of the
                            Patagonians</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl>, which would not be published until
                        1788.</note> y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Grace need not be at the trouble
                    of returning it. it had best be stitched up; &amp; then will be read with more
                    facility. I shall be much obliged to y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Grace for
                    Letting <persName ref="pe0082">Doctor Robertson of Edinburgh</persName> have the
                    perusal, as it may be of use to him in his history of the W.Indies.<note type="editorial">William Robertson never published a discrete work on the
                        West Indies, however his <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0582">
                                <hi rend="italic">History of America</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl> does
                        incorporate material on the <placeName ref="pl0704">West Indies</placeName>
                        and <placeName ref="pl1179">Patagonia</placeName>. <persName ref="pe0580">Thomas Falkner's</persName>
                        <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0439">
                                <hi rend="italic">A Description
                                    of Patagonia </hi>
                            </title>(1774)</bibl> is cited by Robertson in
                        his <hi rend="italic">History of America</hi> (p.406n); Falkner was also the
                        primary source for Pennant's <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0033">
                                <hi rend="italic">Of the Patagonians</hi>
                            </title> (1788)</bibl>. See
                        also Pennant's <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0041">
                                <hi rend="italic">Literary Life</hi>
                            </title>
                            <biblScope unit="page">pp.47-69</biblScope>.</bibl>
                    </note> But I am very
                    desirous that it sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> not get into any hands who may
                    copy or publish it; for it w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> grieve me to have it
                    appear incomplete as I fear it yet is.</p>
                <p>My respectfull compliments attend <persName ref="pe0577">the
                    Dutchess</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am my Lord <lb/>Y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Grace's much
                        obliged <lb/>&amp; obedient Humble Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Thomas
                        Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <dateline>Downing Nov<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1772.</dateline>
                </closer>
